leads to worse health outcomes and lower life expectancy for people of color. By presenting evidence of discrimination in housing, education, employment, and the criminal justice system, Dayna Bowen Matthew shows how racial inequality pervades American society and the multitude of ways that this undermines the health of minority populations. The author provides a clear path forward for overcoming these massive barriers to health and ensuring that everyone has an equal opportunity to be healthy. She encourages health providers to take a leading role in the fight to dismantle the structural inequities their patients face. A compelling and essential read, Just Health helps us to understand how racial inequality damages the health of our minority communities and explains what we can do to fight back.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxHealth and hygienexSocial aspects. 0aDiscrimination in medical carezUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxMedical carezUnited States. 0aSocial medicine. 7aLAW / Health.2bisacsh  a14th Amendment.  aAnti-Racism.  aAsthma.  aCOVID-19.  aCivil Rights.  aColonial.  aCommunity.  aDehumanization.  aDiscipline disparities.  aDiscrimination.  aDisparate Impact.  aEducation.  aEnvironmental justice.  aEqual Educational Opportunities Act.  aEqual Protection.  aEquality.  aFair Housing Act.  aFlint, Michigan.  aFood Insecurity.  aHealth Disparities.  aHealth Equity.  aHousing.  aHuman Rights.  aIncarceration.  aIncome Inequality.  aInequality.  aJim Crow.  aMedical Committee for Civil Rights.  aMedical Legal Partnership.  aPublic Health.  aRacism.  aReparations.  aResidential Segregation.  aSegregation.  aSocial Determinants of Health.  aSouth Bronx.  aStructural Inequality.  aStructural Racism.  aStructural r